{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0e2cf0d7-c0b0-4f14-a57a-fd6005a2618c","content":"In .NET MAUI, `Application` no longer has `OnStart`/`OnSleep`/`OnResume`. The lifecycle moved to the **`Window`** class.\n\n**Option 1 — Subscribe to `Window` events in `App.xaml.cs`:**\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created  += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };\n    window.Stopped  += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };\n    window.Resumed  += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };\n    window.Destroying += (s, e) => { /* cleanup */ };\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Subclass `Window` and override directly:**\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated()    { /* OnStart */  }\n    protected override void OnStopped()    { /* OnSleep */  }\n    protected override void OnResumed()    { /* OnResume */ }\n}\n```\n\nThen in `App.xaml.cs`:\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    => new MyWindow(new AppShell());\n```\n\n**Mapping summary:**\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI (Window) |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart` | `Created` / `OnCreated` |\n| `OnSleep` | `Stopped` / `OnStopped` |\n| `OnResume` | `Resumed` / `OnResumed` |\n\nThere's also `OnBackgrounding` and `OnDeactivated` for more granular control. For **platform-specific** lifecycle hooks, use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents()` in `MauiProgram.cs`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f4978904-7b6d-4b65-a103-4da85f621264","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` in your `Application` subclass.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. The `Application` class still exists, but the recommended approach is to use the **Window lifecycle events** or the **cross-platform lifecycle events** via the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`, or override `CreateWindow` and hook into `Window` events.\n \nThe newer pattern uses `Window` lifecycle events like `Created`, `Resumed`, `Stopped`, and `Destroying`, or you can configure platform-specific lifecycle events through `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`. While `Application.OnStart`, `Application.OnSleep`, and `Application.OnResume` don't exist in .NET MAUI, the `Window` events provide the equivalent functionality with a more modern architecture. → `Window.Stopped` event or override `OnStopped()` / `OnBackgrounding()` for the sleep state, and `Window.Resumed` event or override `OnResumed()` for resuming. I can implement this by either overriding `CreateWindow()` in the `App` class and subscribing to window events, creating a custom `Window` subclass with overridden lifecycle methods, or using `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` for platform-specific behavior.","outputTokens":1109,"requestId":"9BD1:13440B:620C349:6D3DA1B:69EC0EF4"},"id":"88fac397-fcf9-42a3-8a45-5bf1eb6c75b9","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:47:03.274Z","parentId":"3150fa59-602e-4250-bd6a-c9dac2f06c16"}
